[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Cloud storage services may be accessed through a colocated cloud computing service, a web service application programming interface (API) or by applications that use the API, such as cloud desktop storage, a cloud storage gateway or Web-based content management systems.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Cloud computing is believed to have been invented by J.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Licklider in the 1960s with his work on ARPANET to connect people and data from anywhere at any time.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] In 1983, CompuServe offered its consumer users a small amount of disk space that could be used to store any files they chose to upload.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] In 1994, AT&T launched PersonaLink Services, an online platform for personal and business communication and entrepreneurship.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] In 2005, Box announced an online file sharing and personal cloud content management service for businesses.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Alibaba Cloud was launched in September 2009, three years after AWS.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] As of 2024, Gartner ranked cloud storage platforms as follows: AWS, Google, Microsoft, Oracle, Alibaba, IBM, Huawei and Tencent.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] These account for 97% of the global cloud services market.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] This rating was based on ability to execute in market and innovation vision.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] In 2023, 80% of China's technology companies and half of AI LLM companies ran on Alibaba Cloud while in the US dominance belonged to AWS with 31 to 50% share.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] In 2026, Alibaba is scheduled to spend more than 300 million yuan, about $52 billion, on artificial intelligence and cloud infrastructure over the next three years, a figure much larger than the amount spent the previous year.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Data centers will also be expanding, and AI models like Qwen.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Alibaba's CEO, Eddie Wu, describes the amount spent as the largest to date on cloud and AI.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Also, he explained that they expect much of the internal AI workload to run on Alibaba Cloud.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Spending will include specific items such as GPU-like accelerators and large-scale data centers to support internal workloads and external client functions, underscoring Alibaba's pivot from e-commerce to cloud infrastructure.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Cloud storage is based on highly virtualized infrastructure and is like broader cloud computing in terms of interfaces, near-instant elasticity and scalability, multi-tenancy, and metered resources.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Cloud storage services can be used from an off-premises service (Amazon S3) or deployed on-premises (ViON Capacity Services).
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] There are three types of cloud storage: a hosted object storage service, file storage, and block storage.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Each of these cloud storage types offer their own unique advantages.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Security of stored data and data in transit may be a concern when storing sensitive data at a cloud storage provider.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Outsourcing data storage increases the attack surface area.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Cloud storage is a rich resource for both hackers and national security agencies.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Because the cloud holds data from many different users and organizations, hackers see it as a very valuable target.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] The number of people with access to the data who could be compromised (e.g., bribed, or coerced) increases dramatically.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Decryption keys that are kept by the service user, as opposed to the service provider, limit access to data by service provider employees.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] As for sharing multiple data in the cloud with multiple users, a large number of keys has to be distributed to users via secure channels for decryption, also it has to be securely stored and managed by the users in their devices.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Storing these keys requires rather expensive secure storage.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] To overcome that, key-aggregate cryptosystem can be used.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] It increases the number of networks over which the data travels.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Instead of just a local area network (LAN) or storage area network (SAN), data stored on a cloud requires a WAN (wide area network) to connect them both.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] By sharing storage and networks with many other users/customers it is possible for other customers to access your data.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Sometimes because of erroneous actions, faulty equipment, a bug and sometimes because of criminal intent.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] This risk applies to all types of storage and not only cloud storage.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] The risk of having data read during transmission can be mitigated through encryption technology.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Encryption in transit protects data as it is being transmitted to and from the cloud service.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Encryption at rest protects data that is stored at the service provider.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Encrypting data in an on-premises cloud service on-ramp system can provide both kinds of encryption protection.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] There are several options available to avoid security issues.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] One option is to use a private cloud instead of a public cloud.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Another option is to ingest data in an encrypted format where the key is held within the on-premise infrastructure.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] To this end, access is often by use of on-premise cloud storage gateways that have options to encrypt the data prior to transfer.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Typically, cloud storage Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by other services offered within the same provider.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, service providers typically do not offer monetary compensation.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage is a term for a storage infrastructure that uses a combination of on-premises storage resources with cloud storage.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] The on-premises storage is usually managed by the organization, while the public cloud storage provider is responsible for the management and security of the data stored in the cloud.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage can be implemented by an on-premises cloud storage gateway that presents a file system or object storage interface that users can access in the same way they would access a local storage system.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] The cloud storage gateway transparently transfers the data to and from the cloud storage service, providing low latency access to the data through a local cache.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage can be used to supplement an organization's internal storage resources, or it can be used as the primary storage infrastructure.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] In either case, hybrid cloud storage can provide organizations with greater flexibility and scalability than traditional on-premises storage infrastructure.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] There are several benefits to using hybrid cloud storage, including the ability to cache frequently used data on-site for quick access, while inactive cold data is stored off-site in the cloud.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] This can save space, reduce storage costs and improve performance.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cloud-storage] Additionally, hybrid cloud storage can provide organizations with greater redundancy and fault tolerance, as data is stored in both on-premises and cloud storage infrastructure.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] A **Canonical Name** (**CNAME**) **record** is a type of resource record in the Domain Name System (DNS) that maps one domain name (an alias) to another (the **canonical name**).
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] This can prove convenient when running multiple services (like an FTP server *and* a web server, each running on different ports) from a single IP address.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] One can, for example, use CNAME records to point *ftp.example.com* and *www.example.com* to the DNS entry for *example.com*, which in turn has an A record which points to the IP address.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] Then, if the IP address ever changes, one only has to record the change in one place within the network: in the DNS A record for *example.com*.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] CNAME records must always point to another domain name, never directly to an IP address.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] DNS CNAME records are specified in RFC 1034 and clarified in Section 10 of RFC 2181.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] CNAME records are handled specially in the domain name system and have several restrictions on their use.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] When a DNS resolver encounters a CNAME record while looking for a regular resource record, it will restart the query using the canonical name instead of the original name.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] However, if the resolver is specifically told to look for CNAME records, the canonical name (right-hand side) is returned, rather than restarting the query.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] The canonical name that a CNAME record points to can be anywhere in the DNS, whether local or on a remote server in a different DNS zone.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] When an A record lookup for *bar.example.com* is carried out, the resolver will see a CNAME record and restart the lookup for *foo.example.com* and will then return 192.0.2.23.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] With a CNAME record, one can point a name such as "*bar.example.com*" to "*foo.example.com*".
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] Because of this, during casual discussion, the "*bar.example.com.*" (left-hand) side of a DNS entry can be incorrectly identified as "the CNAME" or "a CNAME".
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] The canonical (true) name of "*bar.example.com*" is "*foo.example.com*".
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] Because CNAME stands for Canonical Name, the right-hand side is the *actual* "CNAME"; on the same side as the address "A".
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] This confusion is specifically mentioned in RFC 2181, "Clarifications to the DNS Specification".
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] The left-hand label is an alias for the right-hand side (the RDATA portion), which *is* (or should be) a canonical name.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] This may be read as saying that "*bar.example.com*" is an alias for the canonical name (CNAME) "*foo.example.com*".
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] A client will request "*bar.example.com*" and the answer will be "*foo.example.com*".
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] A **DNAME record** or **Delegation Name record** is defined by RFC 6672 (original RFC 2672 is now obsolete).
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] The DNAME record provides redirection (alias) for a subtree of the domain name tree in the DNS.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] That is, all names that end with a particular suffix are redirected to another part of the DNS.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] In contrast, the CNAME record creates an alias for a single name and not its subdomains.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] Like the CNAME record, the DNS lookup will continue by retrying the lookup with the new name.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] The name server synthesizes a CNAME record to actually apply the DNAME record to the requested name—CNAMEs for every node on a subtree have the same effect as a DNAME for the entire subtree.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] An **A** record lookup for *foo.example.com* will return no data because a DNAME is not a CNAME and there is no A record directly at *foo*.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] However, a lookup for *xyzzy.**foo**.example.com* will be DNAME mapped and return the **A** record for *xyzzy.**bar**.example.com*, which is 192.0.2.24; if the DNAME record had been a CNAME record, this request would have returned name not found.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] Lastly, a request for *foobar.foo.example.com* would be DNAME mapped and return 192.0.2.25.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] Several managed DNS platforms implement a non-standard ALIAS or ANAME record type.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] These pseudo records are managed by DNS administrators like CNAME records, but are published and resolved by (some) DNS clients like A records.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] ANAME records are typically configured to point to another domain, but when queried by a client, answer with an IP address.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] While ANAME record types were submitted for standardization, there are other non-conforming implementations, so they can do whatever the owner of the DNS platform chooses, including existing at the apex of a zone and existing for domains that receive mail.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] The main advantage of ANAME records over CNAME records is that they can be used on a zone apex, while a standards-following resolver will not treat domain names with CNAME records as a zone apex.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] Also, while a DNS client requires at least two queries to resolve a CNAME to an A record to an IP address, an ANAME will shift the second and subsequent query to the server.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] If the DNS server can resolve the A record and cache the requested IP address more efficiently and with less latency than its DNS clients can, then the DNS client can resolve the query faster.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] The ANAME record type was submitted as a draft standard to IETF.
[src:subdomain-takeover/cname-record] However, the latest draft document expired in January 2020 and has been superseded by a series of proposals, the most recent of which is the one for the SVCB and HTTPS record types.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] Domain hijacking can be done in several ways, generally by unauthorized access to, or exploiting a vulnerability in the domain name registrar's system, through social engineering, or getting into the domain owner's email account that is associated with the domain name registration.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] A frequent tactic used by domain hijackers is to use acquired personal information about the actual domain owner to impersonate them and persuade the domain registrar to modify the registration information and/or transfer the domain to another registrar, a form of identity theft.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] Once this has been done, the hijacker has full control of the domain and can use it or sell it to a third party.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] Other methods include email vulnerability, vulnerability at the domain-registration level, keyloggers, and phishing sites.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] Responses to discovered hijackings vary; sometimes the registration information can be returned to its original state by the current registrar, but this may be more difficult if the domain name was transferred to another registrar, particularly if that registrar resides in another country.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] If the stolen domain name has been transferred to another registrar, the losing registrar may invoke ICANN's Registrar Transfer Dispute Resolution Policy to seek the return of the domain.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] In some cases, the losing registrar for the domain name is not able to regain control over the domain, and the domain name owner may need to pursue legal action to obtain the court ordered return of the domain.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] In some jurisdictions, police may arrest cybercriminals involved, or prosecutors may file indictments.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] Although the legal status of domain hijacking was formerly thought to be unclear, certain U.S. federal courts in particular have begun to accept causes of action seeking the return of stolen domain names.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] For this reason, court actions seeking the recovery of stolen domain names are most frequently filed in the location of the relevant domain registry.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] In some cases, victims have pursued recovery of stolen domain names through ICANN's Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (UDRP), but a number of UDRP panels have ruled that the policy is not appropriate for cases involving domain theft.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] Additionally, police may arrest cybercriminals involved.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] ICANN imposes a 60-day waiting period between a change in registration information and a transfer to another registrar.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] This is intended to make domain hijacking more difficult, since a transferred domain is much more difficult to reclaim, and it is more likely that the original registrant will discover the change in that period and alert the registrar.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-hijacking] Extensible Provisioning Protocol is used for many TLD registries, and uses an authorization code issued exclusively to the domain registrant as a security measure to prevent unauthorized transfers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The **Domain Name System** (**DNS**) is a hierarchical and distributed name service that provides a naming system for computers, services, and other resources on the Internet or other Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] It associates various information with *domain names* (identification strings) assigned to each of the associated entities.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Most prominently, it translates readily memorized domain names to the numerical IP addresses needed for locating and identifying computer services and devices with the underlying network protocols.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System has been an essential component of the functionality of the Internet since 1985.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System delegates the responsibility of assigning domain names and mapping those names to Internet resources by designating authoritative name servers for each domain.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Network administrators may delegate authority over subdomains of their allocated name space to other name servers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This mechanism provides distributed and fault-tolerant service and was designed to avoid a single large central database.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In addition, the DNS specifies the technical functionality of the database service that is at its core.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] It defines the DNS protocol, a detailed specification of the data structures and data communication exchanges used in the DNS, as part of the Internet protocol suite.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The Internet maintains two principal namespaces, the domain name hierarchy and the IP address spaces.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System maintains the domain name hierarchy and provides translation services between it and the address spaces.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Internet name servers and a communication protocol implement the Domain Name System.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A DNS name server is a server that stores the DNS records for a domain; a DNS name server responds with answers to queries against its database.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The most common types of records stored in the DNS database are for start of authority (SOA), IP addresses (A and AAAA), SMTP mail exchangers (MX), name servers (NS), pointers for reverse DNS lookups (PTR), and domain name aliases (CNAME).
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Although not intended to be a general-purpose database, DNS has been expanded over time to store records for other types of data for either automatic lookups, such as DNSSEC records, or for human queries such as *responsible person* (RP) records.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] As a general-purpose database, the DNS has also been used in combating unsolicited email (spam) by storing blocklists.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The DNS database is conventionally stored in a structured text file, the zone file, but other database systems are common.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System originally used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) as transport over IP.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Reliability, security, and privacy concerns spawned the use of the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) as well as numerous other protocol developments.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] An often-used analogy to explain the DNS is that it serves as the phone book for the Internet by translating human-friendly computer hostnames into IP addresses.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The DNS can be quickly and transparently updated, allowing a service's location on the network to change without affecting the end users, who continue to use the same hostname.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Users take advantage of this when they use meaningful Uniform Resource Locators (URLs) and e-mail addresses without having to know how the computer actually locates the services.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] An important and ubiquitous function of the DNS is its central role in distributed Internet services such as cloud services and content delivery networks.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] When a user accesses a distributed Internet service using a URL, the domain name of the URL is translated to the IP address of a server that is proximal to the user.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The key functionality of the DNS exploited here is that different users can *simultaneously* receive different translations for the *same* domain name, a key point of divergence from a traditional phone-book view of the DNS.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This process of using the DNS to assign proximal servers to users is key to providing faster and more reliable responses on the Internet and is widely used by most major Internet services.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The DNS reflects the structure of administrative responsibility on the Internet.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Each subdomain is a zone of administrative autonomy delegated to a manager.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For zones operated by a registry, administrative information is often complemented by the registry's RDAP and WHOIS services.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] That data can be used to gain insight on, and track responsibility for, a given host on the Internet.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Using a simpler, more memorable name in place of a host's numerical address dates back to the ARPANET era.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International) maintained a text file named HOSTS.TXT that mapped host names to the numerical addresses of computers on the ARPANET.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Elizabeth Feinler developed and maintained the first ARPANET directory.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Maintenance of numerical addresses, called the Assigned Numbers List, was handled by Jon Postel at the University of Southern California's Information Sciences Institute (ISI), whose team worked closely with SRI.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Computers, including their hostnames and addresses, were added to the primary file by contacting the SRI Network Information Center (NIC), directed by Feinler, via telephone during business hours.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Later, Feinler set up a WHOIS directory on a server in the NIC for retrieval of information about resources, contacts, and entities.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] She and her team developed the concept of domains.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Feinler suggested that domains should be based on the location of the physical address of the computer.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Computers at educational institutions would have the domain *edu*, for example.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] She and her team managed the Host Naming Registry from 1972 to 1989.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] By the early 1980s, maintaining a single, centralized host table had become slow and unwieldy and the emerging network required an automated naming system to address technical and personnel issues.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Postel directed the task of forging a compromise between five competing proposals of solutions to Paul Mockapetris.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Mockapetris instead created the Domain Name System in 1983 while at the University of Southern California.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The Internet Engineering Task Force published the original specifications in RFC 882 and RFC 883 in November 1983.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] These were updated in RFC 973 in January 1986.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In 1984, four UC Berkeley students, Douglas Terry, Mark Painter, David Riggle, and Songnian Zhou, wrote the first Unix name server implementation for the Berkeley Internet Name Domain, commonly referred to as BIND.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In 1985, Kevin Dunlap of DEC substantially revised the DNS implementation.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Mike Karels, Phil Almquist, and Paul Vixie then took over BIND maintenance.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Internet Systems Consortium was founded in 1994 by Rick Adams, Paul Vixie, and Carl Malamud, expressly to provide a home for BIND development and maintenance.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] BIND versions from 4.9.3 onward were developed and maintained by ISC, with support provided by ISC's sponsors.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] As co-architects/programmers, Bob Halley and Paul Vixie released the first production-ready version of BIND version 8 in May 1997.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Since 2000, over 43 different core developers have worked on BIND.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In November 1987, RFC 1034 and RFC 1035 superseded the 1983 DNS specifications.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Several additional Request for Comments have proposed extensions to the core DNS protocols.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The domain name space consists of a tree data structure.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Each node or leaf in the tree has a *label* and zero or more *resource records* (RR), which hold information associated with the domain name.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The domain name itself consists of the label, concatenated with the name of its parent node on the right, separated by a dot.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The tree sub-divides into *zones* beginning at the root zone.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A DNS zone may consist of as many domains and subdomains as the zone manager chooses.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNS can also be partitioned according to *class* where the separate classes can be thought of as an array of parallel namespace trees.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Administrative responsibility for any zone may be divided by creating additional zones.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Authority over the new zone is said to be *delegated* to a designated name server.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The parent zone ceases to be authoritative for the new zone.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The definitive descriptions of the rules for forming domain names appear in RFC 1035, RFC 1123, RFC 2181, and RFC 5892.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A domain name consists of one or more parts, technically called *labels*, that are conventionally concatenated, and delimited by dots, such as example.com.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The right-most label conveys the top-level domain; for example, the domain name www.example.com belongs to the top-level domain *com*.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The hierarchy of domains descends from right to left; each label to the left specifies a subdivision, or subdomain of the domain to the right.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For example, the label *example* specifies a subdomain of the *com* domain, and *www* is a subdomain of example.com.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This tree of subdivisions may have up to 127 levels.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A label may contain zero to 63 characters, because the length is only allowed to take 6 bits.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The null label of length zero is reserved for the root zone.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The full domain name may not exceed the length of 253 characters in its textual representation (or 254 with the trailing dot).
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In the internal binary representation of the DNS this maximum length of 253 requires 255 octets of storage, as it also stores the length of the first of many labels and adds last null byte.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] 255 length is only achieved with at least 6 labels (counting the last null label).
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Although no technical limitation exists to prevent domain name labels from using any character that is representable by an octet, hostnames use a preferred format and character set.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The characters allowed in labels are a subset of the ASCII character set, consisting of characters *a* through *z*, *A* through *Z*, digits *0* through *9*, and hyphen.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This rule is known as the *LDH rule* (letters, digits, hyphen).
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Domain names are interpreted in a case-independent manner.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Labels may not start or end with a hyphen.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] An additional rule requires that top-level domain names should not be all-numeric.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The limited set of ASCII characters permitted in the DNS prevented the representation of names and words of many languages in their native alphabets or scripts.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] To make this possible, ICANN approved the Internationalizing Domain Names in Applications (IDNA) system, by which user applications, such as web browsers, map Unicode strings into the valid DNS character set using Punycode.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In 2009, ICANN approved the installation of internationalized domain name country code top-level domains (*ccTLD*s).
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In addition, many registries of the existing top-level domain names (*TLD*s) have adopted the IDNA system, guided by RFC 5890, RFC 5891, RFC 5892, RFC 5893.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System is maintained by a distributed database system, which uses the client–server model.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The nodes of this database are the name servers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Each domain has at least one authoritative DNS server that publishes information about that domain and the name servers of any domains subordinate to it.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The top of the hierarchy is served by the root name servers, the servers to query when looking up (*resolving*) a TLD.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] An authoritative name server can either be a *primary* server or a *secondary* server.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Historically the terms *master/slave* and *primary/secondary* were sometimes used interchangeably but the current practice is to use the latter form.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A primary server is a server that stores the original copies of all zone records.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A secondary server uses a special automatic updating mechanism in the DNS protocol in communication with its primary to maintain an identical copy of the primary records.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Every DNS zone must be assigned a set of authoritative name servers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This set of servers is stored in the parent domain zone with name server (NS) records.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] An authoritative server indicates its status of supplying definitive answers, deemed *authoritative*, by setting a protocol flag, called the "*Authoritative Answer*" (*AA*) bit in its responses.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] When a name server is designated as the authoritative server for a domain name for which it does not have authoritative data, it presents a type of error called a "lame delegation" or "lame response".
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Domain name resolvers determine the domain name servers responsible for the domain name in question by a sequence of queries starting with the right-most (top-level) domain label.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For proper operation of its domain name resolver, a network host is configured with an initial cache (*hints*) of the known addresses of the root name servers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The hints are updated periodically by an administrator by retrieving a dataset from a reliable source.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Assuming the resolver has no cached records to accelerate the process, the resolution process starts with a query to one of the root servers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In typical operation, the root servers do not answer directly, but respond with a referral to more authoritative servers, e.g., a query for "www.wikipedia.org" is referred to the *org* servers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The resolver now queries the servers referred to, and iteratively repeats this process until it receives an authoritative answer.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The diagram illustrates this process for the host that is named by the fully qualified domain name "www.wikipedia.org".
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This mechanism would place a large traffic burden on the root servers, if every resolution on the Internet required starting at the root.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In practice caching is used in DNS servers to off-load the root servers, and as a result, root name servers actually are involved in only a relatively small fraction of all requests.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In theory, authoritative name servers are sufficient for the operation of the Internet.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] However, with only authoritative name servers operating, every DNS query must start with recursive queries at the root zone of the Domain Name System and each user system would have to implement resolver software capable of recursive operation.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Typically, such caching DNS servers also implement the recursive algorithm necessary to resolve a given name starting with the DNS root through to the authoritative name servers of the queried domain.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] With this function implemented in the name server, user applications gain efficiency in design and operation.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The combination of DNS caching and recursive functions in a name server is not mandatory; the functions can be implemented independently in servers for special purposes.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Internet service providers (ISP) typically provide recursive and caching name servers for their customers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In addition, many home networking routers implement DNS caches and recursion to improve efficiency in the local network.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The client side of the DNS is called a DNS resolver.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A resolver is responsible for initiating and sequencing the queries that ultimately lead to a full resolution (translation) of the resource sought, e.g., translation of a domain name into an IP address.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers are classified by a variety of query methods, such as *recursive*, *non-recursive*, and *iterative*.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A resolution process may use a combination of these methods.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In a *non-recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a DNS server that provides a record either for which the server is authoritative, or it provides a partial result without querying other servers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In case of a caching DNS resolver, the non-recursive query of its local DNS cache delivers a result and reduces the load on upstream DNS servers by caching DNS resource records for a period of time after an initial response from upstream DNS servers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In a *recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a single DNS server, which may in turn query other DNS servers on behalf of the requester.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For example, a simple stub resolver running on a home router typically makes a recursive query to the DNS server run by the user's ISP.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A recursive query is one for which the DNS server answers the query completely by querying other name servers as needed.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In typical operation, a client issues a recursive query to a caching recursive DNS server, which subsequently issues non-recursive queries to determine the answer and send a single answer back to the client.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The resolver, or another DNS server acting recursively on behalf of the resolver, negotiates use of recursive service using bits in the query headers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNS servers are not required to support recursive queries.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The *iterative query* procedure is a process in which a DNS resolver queries a chain of one or more DNS servers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Each server refers the client to the next server in the chain, until the current server can fully resolve the request.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For example, a possible resolution of www.example.com would query a global root server, then a "com" server, and finally an "example.com" server.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Name servers in delegations are identified by name, rather than by IP address.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This means that a resolving name server must issue another DNS request to discover the IP address of the server to which it has been referred.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] If the name given in the delegation is a subdomain of the domain for which the delegation is being provided, there is a circular dependency.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In this case, the name server providing the delegation must also provide one or more IP addresses for the authoritative name server mentioned in the delegation.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The delegating name server provides this glue in the form of records in the *additional section* of the DNS response, and provides the delegation in the *authority section* of the response.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A glue record is a combination of the name server and IP address.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For example, if the authoritative name server for example.org is ns1.example.org, a computer trying to resolve www.example.org first resolves ns1.example.org.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] As ns1 is contained in example.org, this requires resolving example.org first, which presents a circular dependency.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] To break the dependency, the name server for the top level domain org includes glue along with the delegation for example.org.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The glue records are address records that provide IP addresses for ns1.example.org.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The resolver uses one or more of these IP addresses to query one of the domain's authoritative servers, which allows it to complete the DNS query.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A common approach to reduce the query load on DNS servers is to cache the results of name resolution locally or on intermediary resolver hosts.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Each DNS query result comes with a time to live (TTL), which indicates how long the information remains valid before it needs to be discarded or refreshed.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This TTL is determined by the administrator of the authoritative DNS server and can range from a few seconds to several days or even weeks.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] As a result of this distributed caching architecture, changes to DNS records do not propagate throughout the network immediately, but require all caches to expire and to be refreshed after the TTL.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] RFC 1912 conveys basic rules for determining appropriate TTL values.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Some resolvers may override TTL values, as the protocol supports caching for up to sixty-eight years or no caching at all.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Negative caching, i.e. the caching of the fact of non-existence of a record, is determined by name servers authoritative for a zone which must include the Start of Authority (SOA) record when reporting no data of the requested type exists.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The value of the *minimum* field of the SOA record and the TTL of the SOA itself is used to establish the TTL for the negative answer.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A reverse DNS lookup is a query of the DNS for domain names when the IP address is known.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Multiple domain names may be associated with an IP address.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The DNS stores IP addresses in the form of domain names as specially formatted names in pointer (PTR) records within the infrastructure top-level domain arpa.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For IPv6, the reverse lookup domain is ip6.arpa.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The IP address is represented as a name in reverse-ordered octet representation for IPv4, and reverse-ordered nibble representation for IPv6.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] When performing a reverse lookup, the DNS client converts the address into these formats before querying the name for a PTR record following the delegation chain as for any DNS query.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For example, assuming the IPv4 address 208.80.152.2 is assigned to Wikimedia, it is represented as a DNS name in reverse order: 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] When the DNS resolver gets a pointer (PTR) request, it begins by querying the root servers, which point to the servers of American Registry for Internet Numbers (ARIN) for the 208.in-addr.arpa zone.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] ARIN's servers delegate 152.80.208.in-addr.arpa to Wikimedia to which the resolver sends another query for 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa, which results in an authoritative response.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Users generally do not communicate directly with a DNS resolver.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Instead DNS resolution takes place transparently in applications such as web browsers, e-mail clients, and other Internet applications.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] When an application makes a request that requires a domain name lookup, such programs send a resolution request to the DNS resolver in the local operating system, which in turn handles the communications required.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The DNS resolver will almost invariably have a cache (see above) containing recent lookups.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] If the cache can provide the answer to the request, the resolver will return the value in the cache to the program that made the request.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] If the cache does not contain the answer, the resolver will send the request to one or more designated DNS servers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In any event, the name server thus queried will follow the process outlined above, until it either successfully finds a result or does not.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] It then returns its results to the DNS resolver; assuming it has found a result, the resolver duly caches that result for future use, and hands the result back to the software which initiated the request.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Some large ISPs have configured their DNS servers to violate rules, such as by disobeying TTLs, or by indicating that a domain name does not exist just because one of its name servers does not respond.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Some applications such as web browsers maintain an internal DNS cache to avoid repeated lookups via the network.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This practice can add extra difficulty when debugging DNS issues as it obscures the history of such data.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] These caches typically use very short caching times on the order of one minute.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer represents a notable exception: versions up to IE 3.x cache DNS records for 24 hours by default.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer 4.x and later versions (up to IE 8) decrease the default timeout value to half an hour, which may be changed by modifying the default configuration.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] When Google Chrome detects issues with the DNS server it displays a specific error message.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System includes several other functions and features.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Hostnames and IP addresses are not required to match in a one-to-one relationship.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Multiple hostnames may correspond to a single IP address, which is useful in virtual hosting, in which many web sites are served from a single host.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Alternatively, a single hostname may resolve to many IP addresses to facilitate fault tolerance and load distribution to multiple server instances across an enterprise or the global Internet.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNS serves other purposes in addition to translating names to IP addresses.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For instance, mail transfer agents use DNS to find the best mail server to deliver e-mail: An MX record provides a mapping between a domain and a mail exchanger; this can provide an additional layer of fault tolerance and load distribution.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The DNS is used for efficient storage and distribution of IP addresses of block-listed email hosts.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A common method is to place the IP address of the subject host into the sub-domain of a higher level domain name, and to resolve that name to a record that indicates a positive or a negative indication.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] E-mail servers can query blocklist.example to find out if a specific host connecting to them is in the block list.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Many such block lists, either subscription-based or free of cost, are available for use by email administrators and anti-spam software.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] To provide resilience in the event of computer or network failure, multiple DNS servers are usually provided for coverage of each domain.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] At the top level of global DNS, thirteen groups of root name servers exist, with additional "copies" of them distributed worldwide via anycast addressing.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS (DDNS) updates a DNS server with a client IP address on-the-fly, for example, when moving between ISPs or mobile hot spots, or when the IP address changes administratively.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The DNS protocol uses two types of DNS messages, queries and responses; both have the same format.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Each message consists of a header and four sections: question, answer, authority, and an additional space.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A header field (*flags*) controls the content of these four sections.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The header section consists of the following fields: *Identification*, *Flags*, *Number of questions*, *Number of answers*, *Number of authority resource records* (RRs), and *Number of additional RRs*.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Each field is 16 bits long, and appears in the order given.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The identification field is used to match responses with queries.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] After the flags word, the header ends with four 16-bit integers which contain the number of records in each of the sections that follow, in the same order.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Indicates if the message is a query (0) or a reply (1).
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The type can be QUERY (standard query, 0), IQUERY (inverse query, 1), or STATUS (server status request, 2).
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Authoritative Answer, in a response, indicates if the DNS server is authoritative for the queried hostname.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] TrunCation, indicates that this message was truncated due to excessive length.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Recursion Desired, indicates if the client means a recursive query.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Recursion Available, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server supports recursion.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Authentic Data, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server verified the data.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Checking Disabled, in a query, indicates that non-verified data is acceptable in a response.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Response code, can be NOERROR (0), FORMERR (1, Format error), SERVFAIL (2), NXDOMAIN (3, Nonexistent domain), etc.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The question section has a simpler format than the resource record format used in the other sections.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The domain name is broken into discrete labels which are concatenated; each label is prefixed by the length of that label.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System specifies a database of information elements for network resources.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The types of information elements are categorized and organized with a list of DNS record types, the resource records (RRs).
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Each record has a type (name and number), an expiration time (time to live), a class, and type-specific data.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Resource records of the same type are described as a *resource record set* (RRset), having no special ordering.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers return the entire set upon query, but servers may implement round-robin ordering to achieve load balancing.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In contrast, the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) work on the complete set of resource record in canonical order.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The *CLASS* of a record is set to IN (for *Internet*) for common DNS records involving Internet hostnames, servers, or IP addresses.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In addition, the classes Chaos (CH) and Hesiod (HS) exist.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Each class is an independent name space with potentially different delegations of DNS zones.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In addition to resource records defined in a zone file, the domain name system also defines several request types that are used only in communication with other DNS nodes (*on the wire*), such as when performing zone transfers (AXFR/IXFR) or for EDNS (OPT).
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The domain name system supports wildcard DNS records which specify names that start with the *asterisk label*, `*`, e.g., `*.example`.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNS records belonging to wildcard domain names specify rules for generating resource records within a single DNS zone by substituting whole labels with matching components of the query name, including any specified descendants.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For example, in the following configuration, the DNS zone *x.example* specifies that all subdomains, including subdomains of subdomains, of *x.example* use the mail exchanger (MX) *a.x.example*.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The AAAA record for *a.x.example* is needed to specify the mail exchanger IP address.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] As this has the result of excluding this domain name and its subdomains from the wildcard matches, an additional MX record for the subdomain *a.x.example*, as well as a wildcarded MX record for all of its subdomains, must also be defined in the DNS zone.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The role of wildcard records was refined in RFC 4592, because the original definition in RFC 1034 was incomplete and resulted in misinterpretations by implementers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The original DNS protocol had limited provisions for extension with new features.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In 1999, Paul Vixie published in RFC 2671 (superseded by RFC 6891) an extension mechanism, called Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS) that introduced optional protocol elements without increasing overhead when not in use.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This was accomplished through the OPT pseudo-resource record that only exists in wire transmissions of the protocol, but not in any zone files.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Initial extensions were also suggested (EDNS0), such as increasing the DNS message size in UDP datagrams.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS updates use the UPDATE DNS opcode to add or remove resource records dynamically from a zone database maintained on an authoritative DNS server.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This facility is useful to register network clients into the DNS when they boot or become otherwise available on the network.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] As a booting client may be assigned a different IP address each time from a DHCP server, it is not possible to provide static DNS assignments for such clients.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] From the time of its origin in 1983 the DNS has used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) for transport over IP.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Its limitations have motivated numerous protocol developments for reliability, security, privacy, and other criteria, in the following decades.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] UDP reserves port number 53 for servers listening to queries.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Such a query consists of a clear-text request sent in a single UDP packet from the client, responded to with a clear-text reply sent in a single UDP packet from the server.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] When the length of the answer exceeds 512 bytes and both client and server support Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS), larger UDP packets may be used.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Use of DNS over UDP is limited by, among other things, its lack of transport-layer encryption, authentication, reliable delivery, and message length.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In 1989, RFC 1123 specified optional Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transport for DNS queries, replies and, particularly, zone transfers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Via fragmentation of long replies, TCP allows longer responses, reliable delivery, and re-use of long-lived connections between clients and servers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For larger responses, the server refers the client to TCP transport.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNS over TLS emerged as an IETF standard for encrypted DNS in 2016, utilizing Transport Layer Security (TLS) to protect the entire connection, rather than just the DNS payload.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] RFC 7858 specifies that opportunistic encryption and authenticated encryption may be supported, but did not make either server or client authentication mandatory.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNS over HTTPS was developed as a competing standard for DNS query transport in 2018, tunneling DNS query data over HTTPS, which transports HTTP over TLS.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DoH was promoted as a more web-friendly alternative to DNS since, like DNSCrypt, it uses TCP port 443, and thus looks similar to web traffic, though they are easily differentiable in practice without proper padding.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] RFC 9250, published in 2022 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over QUIC.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] It has "privacy properties similar to DNS over TLS (DoT) [...], and latency characteristics similar to classic DNS over UDP".
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This method is not the same as DNS over HTTP/3.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] RFC 9953, published in 2026 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over CoAP.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The "application use case of DoC is inspired by DNS over HTTPS (DoH) (RFC 8484).
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] However, DoC aims for deployment in the constrained Internet of Things (IoT), which usually conflicts with the requirements introduced by HTTPS." DoC outperforms other DNS resolution mechanisms in constrained scenarios.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Oblivious DNS (ODNS) was invented and implemented by researchers at Princeton University and the University of Chicago as an extension to unencrypted DNS, before DoH was standardized and widely deployed.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Apple and Cloudflare subsequently deployed the technology in the context of DoH, as Oblivious DoH (ODoH).
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] ODoH combines ingress/egress separation (invented in ODNS) with DoH's HTTPS tunneling and TLS transport-layer encryption in a single protocol.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNS may be run over virtual private networks (VPNs) and tunneling protocols.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The privacy gains of Oblivious DNS can be garnered through the use of the preexisting Tor network of ingress and egress nodes, paired with the transport-layer encryption provided by TLS.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt uses either TCP port 443, the same port as HTTPS encrypted web traffic, or UDP port 443.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This introduced not only privacy regarding the content of the query, but also a significant measure of firewall-traversal capability.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Privacy of user/query pairs is created, since the ingress node does not know the content of the query, while the egress node does not know the identity of the client.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt was first implemented in production by OpenDNS in December 2011.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] There are several free and open source software implementations that additionally integrate ODoH.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] It is available for a variety of operating systems, including Unix, Apple iOS, Linux, Android, and Windows.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Originally, security concerns were not major design considerations for DNS software or any software for deployment on the early Internet, as the network was not open for participation by the general public.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] However, the expansion of the Internet into the commercial sector in the 1990s changed the requirements for security measures to protect data integrity and user authentication.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Several vulnerability issues were discovered and exploited by malicious users.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] One such issue is DNS cache poisoning, in which data is distributed to caching resolvers under the pretense of being an authoritative origin server, thereby polluting the data store with potentially false information and long expiration times (time-to-live).
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Subsequently, legitimate application requests may be redirected to network hosts operated with malicious intent.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNS responses traditionally do not have a cryptographic signature, leading to many attack possibilities; the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) modify DNS to add support for cryptographically signed responses.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNSCurve has been proposed as an alternative to DNSSEC.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Other extensions, such as TSIG, add support for cryptographic authentication between trusted peers and are commonly used to authorize zone transfer or dynamic update operations.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Techniques such as forward-confirmed reverse DNS can also be used to help validate DNS results.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNS can also "leak" from otherwise secure or private connections, if attention is not paid to their configuration, and at times DNS has been used to bypass firewalls by malicious persons, and exfiltrate data, since it is often seen as innocuous.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Some domain names may be used to achieve spoofing effects.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For example, paypal.com and paypa1.com are different names, yet users may be unable to distinguish them in a graphical user interface depending on the user's chosen typeface.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In many fonts the letter *l* and the numeral *1* look very similar or even identical.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This problem, known as the IDN homograph attack, is acute in systems that support internationalized domain names, as many character codes in ISO 10646 may appear identical on typical computer screens.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This vulnerability is occasionally exploited in phishing.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger is a type of cyber attack technique that uses the DNS to communicate and control malware remotely without relying on conventional protocols that might raise red flags.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The DNSMessenger attack is covert because DNS is primarily used for domain name resolution and is often not closely monitored by network security tools, making it an effective channel for attackers to exploit.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This technique involves the use of DNS TXT records to send commands to infected systems.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Once malware has been surreptitiously installed on a victim's machine, it reaches out to a controlled domain to retrieve commands encoded in DNS text records.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This form of malware communication is stealthy, as DNS requests are usually allowed through firewalls, and because DNS traffic is often seen as benign, these communications can bypass many network security defenses.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger attacks can enable a wide array of malicious activities, from data exfiltration to the delivery of additional payloads, all while remaining under the radar of traditional network security measures.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Understanding and defending against such methods are crucial for maintaining robust cybersecurity.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Originally designed as a public, hierarchical, distributed and heavily cached database, the DNS protocol has no confidentiality controls.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] User queries and nameserver responses are sent unencrypted, enabling network packet sniffing, DNS hijacking, DNS cache poisoning and man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] This deficiency is commonly used by cybercriminals and network operators for marketing purposes, user authentication on captive portals and censorship.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] User privacy is further exposed by proposals for increasing the level of client IP information in DNS queries (RFC 7871) for the benefit of content delivery networks.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Solutions preventing DNS inspection by the local network operator have been criticized for thwarting corporate network security policies and Internet censorship.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Public DNS servers are also criticized for contributing to the centralization of the Internet by placing control over DNS resolution in the hands of the few large companies which can afford to run public resolvers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The right to use a domain name is delegated by domain name registrars which are accredited by the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN) or other organizations such as OpenNIC, that are charged with overseeing the name and number systems of the Internet.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In addition to ICANN, each top-level domain (TLD) is maintained and serviced technically by an administrative organization, operating a registry.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A *registry* is responsible for operating the database of names within its authoritative zone, although the term is most often used for TLDs.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] A *registrant* is a person or organization who asked for domain registration.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The registry receives registration information from each domain name *registrar*, which is authorized (accredited) to assign names in the corresponding zone and publishes the information using the WHOIS protocol.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] As of 2015, usage of RDAP is being considered.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] ICANN publishes the complete list of TLDs, TLD registries, and domain name registrars.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Registrant information associated with domain names is maintained in an online database accessible with the WHOIS service.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For most of the more than 290 country code top-level domains (ccTLDs), the domain registries maintain the WHOIS (Registrant, name servers, expiration dates, etc.) information.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For instance, DENIC, Germany NIC, holds the DE domain data.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] From about 2001, most generic top-level domain (gTLD) registries have adopted this so-called *thick* registry approach, i.e. keeping the WHOIS data in central registries instead of registrar databases.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] For top-level domains on COM and NET, a *thin* registry model is used.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The domain registry (GoDaddy, BigRock and PDR, VeriSign, etc.) holds basic WHOIS data (i.e., registrar and name servers, etc.).
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] On the other hand, organizations, i.e., registrants using ORG, are on the Public Interest Registry exclusively.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] Some domain name registries, often called *network information centers* (NIC), also function as registrars to end-users, in addition to providing access to the WHOIS datasets.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The top-level domain registries, such as for the domains COM, NET, and ORG use a registry-registrar model consisting of many domain name registrars.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] In this method of management, the registry only manages the domain name database and the relationship with the registrars.
[src:subdomain-takeover/domain-name-system] The *registrants* (users of a domain name) are customers of the registrar, in some cases through additional subcontracting of resellers.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] A **fully qualified domain name** (**FQDN**), sometimes also called an **absolute domain name**, is a domain name that specifies its exact location in the tree hierarchy of the Domain Name System (DNS).
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] It specifies all domain levels, including the top-level domain and the root zone.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] A fully qualified domain name is distinguished by its unambiguous DNS zone location in the hierarchy of DNS labels: it can be interpreted in only one way.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] A fully qualified domain name is conventionally written as a list of domain labels separated using the full stop "`.`" character (*dot* or *period*).
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] The top of the hierarchy in an FQDN begins with the rightmost label.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] For instance, in the FQDN `somehost.example.com`, `com` is a label directly under the root zone, `example` is nested under `com`, and finally `somehost` is nested under `example.com`.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] The topmost layer of every domain name is the DNS root zone, which is expressed as an empty label and can be represented in an FQDN with a trailing dot, such as `somehost.example.com.`.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] A trailing dot is generally implied and often omitted by most applications.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] Trailing dots are required by the standard format for DNS zone files, as well as to disambiguate cases where an FQDN does not contain any other label separators, such as the FQDNs for the root zone itself and any top-level domain.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] The length of each label must be between 1 and 63 octets, and the full domain name is limited to 255 octets, full stops included.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] A **relative domain name** is a domain name which does not include all labels.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] It may also be referred to as a partially-qualified domain name, or PQDN.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] Hostnames can be used as relative domain names.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] Dot-separated fully qualified domain names are the primarily used form for human-readable representations of a domain name.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] Dot-separated domain names are not used in the internal representation of labels in a DNS message but are used to reference domains in some TXT records and can appear in resolver configurations, system hosts files, and URLs.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] Web addresses typically use FQDNs to represent the host, as it ensures the address will be interpreted identically on any network.
[src:subdomain-takeover/fully-qualified-domain-name] Relative hostnames are allowed by some protocols, including HTTP, but disallowed by others, such as the Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP).
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] The Web Security Testing Guide (WSTG) Project produces the premier cybersecurity testing resource for web application developers and security professionals.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] The WSTG is a comprehensive guide to testing the security of web applications and web services.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] Created by the collaborative efforts of cybersecurity professionals and dedicated volunteers, the WSTG provides a framework of best practices used by penetration testers and organizations all over the world.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] Any contributions to the guide itself should be made via the guide’s project repo.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] (:stop_sign:) Contributions should only be made in the proper repo against the latest content.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] Please don’t open PRs here for versioned or stable content, they represent point-in-time state.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] View the always-current stable version at stable.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] We are currently developing release version 5.0.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] You can read the latest development documents in our official GitHub repository or view the bleeding-edge content at latest.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] v4.2 is currently available as a web-hosted release and PDF.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] Previous releases are available as PDFs and in some cases web content via the **Release Versions** tab.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] Each scenario has an identifier in the format `WSTG-<category>-<number>`, where: ‘category’ is a 4 character upper case string that identifies the type of test or weakness, and ‘number’ is a zero-padded numeric value from 01 to 99.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] For example:`WSTG-INFO-02` is the second Information Gathering test.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] The identifiers may change between versions therefore it is preferable that other documents, reports, or tools use the format: `WSTG-<version>-<category>-<number>`, where: ‘version’ is the version tag with punctuation removed.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] For example: `WSTG-v41-INFO-02` would be understood to mean specifically the second Information Gathering test from version 4.1.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] If identifiers are used without including the `<version>` element then they should be assumed to refer to the latest Web Security Testing Guide content.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] Obviously as the guide grows and changes this becomes problematic, which is why writers or developers should include the version element.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] Linking to Web Security Testing Guide scenarios should be done using versioned links not `stable` or `latest` which will definitely change with time.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] However, it is the project team’s intention that versioned links not change.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] For example: `https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/v42/4-Web_Application_Security_Testing/01-Information_Gathering/02-Fingerprint_Web_Server`.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] Note: the `v42` element refers to version 4.2.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] Version 4.2 introduces new testing scenarios, updates existing chapters, and offers an improved writing style and chapter layout.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] Version 4.1 serves as a post-migration stable version under the new GitHub repository workflow.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] A printed book is also made available for purchase.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] View a presentation (PPT) previewing the release at the OWASP EU Summit 2008 in Portugal.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] The guide is also available in Word Document format in English (ZIP) as well as Word Document format translation in Spanish (ZIP).
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] Version 1.1 is released as the *OWASP Web Application Penetration Checklist*.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] Historical archives of the Mailman owasp-testing mailing list are available to view or download.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] We are actively inviting new contributors to help keep the WSTG up to date!
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] You can get started at our official GitHub repository.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] To report issues or make suggestions for the WSTG, please use GitHub Issues.
[src:subdomain-takeover/www-project-web-security-testing-guide] Join this project’s channel, #testing-guide.
